div.p:
“Papa, don't you suppose I know gold from brass? don't I know a gentleman when I
                    have the luck to see one? My friend had no ditchwater in his veins;
                    he had a decidedly warlike air too, and you know, dad, you and I have a penchant for soldiers, haven't we?”

“Trouble, a fiddlestick; I shall be glad of an excuse to air my brains a bit; I
                    think some of the fluff and flue of Coxe's cotton mills is getting into them;
                    but by to‐morrow!”

“News! oh yes, lots; the funds have fallen to 84; and the Bishop of — is dead;
                    and the eldest Miss Coxe is going to be married—to me—at least, so I heard this
                    morning.”

“I don't know what she thinks about me, I'm sure; nothing particularly
                    flattering, I fancy. But she thinks that you must be engaged to Amaryllis Coxe;
                    at least, she said so this morning.”
